            <h2 class="text-center">Probation and Expected Behaviour</h2>

            <div id="subcol-1" class="col-sm-6 col-md-6">
                <h3 class="text-centre">Probation</h3>

                <p>To ensure your transition into our unit is as smooth and enjoyable as possible, each new member
                    completes
                    a four week probation period. During this time, you will hold the rank of Recruit or Private,
                    depending on your completion of Basic Training. This is to allow more experienced members of the
                    unit to help you settle in. We've found that this is the best way of getting newbies up to
                    speed.</p>

                <p>The probation period of new members also ensures SOCOMD remains aligned with its mission statement
                    and
                    also helps us to ensure that nobody is dropped into a situation they haven't been trained for. Once
                    the
                    probation period expires, you will have learned enough to stand on your own, and alongside fellow
                    unit
                    members.</p>

                <p>There are no exceptions for probationary periods. Everyone has to start from the bottom, it ensures
                    that
                    all members know what it's like to be a recruit, and what a recruit needs to succeed in becoming a
                    full
                    member of the group.</p>
            </div>
            <div id="subcol-2" class="col-sm-6 col-md-6">
                <h3 class="text-centre">Expected Behaviour</h3>

                <p><b>Just be an adult – it’s really that simple!</b> The behaviour we expect from you is that you
                    listen,
                    take direction from our Officers and NCOs and embrace the same values we do. This is applicable
                    to
                    both new recruits and full members. We are all here to have a good time, but once we deploy it’s
                    time to put our game faces on and work in an authentic way, that fulfils our values, goals and
                    culture.
                    Members who don't share these values, may be asked to leave. Nobody enjoys that, but it happens,
                    it's
                    vital for our continued survival as a unit and as a culture</p>

                <p>We aren't after a mindless drone though, and we aren't a group of professional soldiers either,
                    we do
                    take feedback at the end of every mission, and if you have anything burning you want to say,
                    reach out
                    to someone. The key to getting through the probation period is as simply as listening to what
                    others
                    have to say, treating others with respect, and doing business the same way that we do.</p>

                <p>If you don't think you can follow these guidelines, if you don't feel like you share our values
                    and
                    cultures - we aren't the unit for you. We've discharged members before and we'll keep doing so
                    as needed
                    in the future. It makes nobody happy but it's necessary.</p>
            </div>
